 x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p>当一位（非白人、女性）历史教授对这一说法提出异议时，他<a href="https://x.com/Noahpinion/status/1795141509697708390">指责她从她的权力地位上“压制”</a>他。</p><p>这激怒了推特上的所有人，从谴责沃尔什只是一个更平庸的白人、认为自己比女性和有色人种更有资格的进步派，到嘲笑沃尔什是因为支持不公平的崛起而自找麻烦的保守派。 DEI 政权。各方唯一一致的一点是，他们都鄙视沃尔什。接下来是一场为期一天的大逃杀。沃尔什发表了<a href="https://x.com/dissproportion/status/1795177313937584223">结结巴巴的道歉</a>，但很明显，他实际上相信自己比获得他所申请工作的人更有资格： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8bb0a035-486b-444e-91a1-e203b9203a3e_900x581.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8bb0a035-486b-444e-91a1-e203b9203a3e_900x581.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8bb0a035-486b-444e-91a1-e203b9203a3e_900x581.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8bb0a035-486b-444e-91a1-e203b9203a3e_900x581.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8bb0a035-486b-444e-91a1-e203b9203a3e_900x581.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8bb0a035-486b-444e-91a1-e203b9203a3e_900x581.jpeg" width="654" height="422.1933333333333" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/8bb0a035-486b-444e-91a1-e203b9203a3e_900x581.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:581,&quot;width&quot;:900,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:654,&quot;bytes&quot;:114765,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8bb0a035-486b-444e-91a1-e203b9203a3e_900x581.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8bb0a035-486b-444e-91a1-e203b9203a3e_900x581.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8bb0a035-486b-444e-91a1-e203b9203a3e_900x581.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F8bb0a035-486b-444e-91a1-e203b9203a3e_900x581.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p> I do think the issue of discrimination in academic hiring is slightly interesting, and I&#39;ll get to that in a bit. But what interests me more about the Walsh Affair is how it seems to provide an example of <em>elite overproduction</em> .</p><p> About a year and a half ago, I wrote a post laying out a hypothesis about why there has been so much discontent among the American intellectual elite over the past decade: </p><div class="digest-post-embed" data-attrs="{&quot;nodeId&quot;:&quot;afd51996-9d21-4fef-8f3d-1f4f273d6e2b&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&#8220;We're talented and bright/ We're lonely and uptight/ We've found some lovely ways/ To disappoint&#8221; &#8212; The Weakerthans Here&#8217;s an eye-opening bit of data: The percent of U.S. college students majoring in the humanities has absolutely crashed since 2010.&quot;,&quot;size&quot;:&quot;sm&quot;,&quot;isEditorNode&quot;:true,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;The Elite Overproduction Hypothesis&quot;,&quot;publishedBylines&quot;:[{&quot;id&quot;:8243895,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Noah Smith&quot;,&quot;bio&quot;:&quot;Econ blogger&quot;,&quot;photo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/89fd964a-586f-461a-9f5a-ea4587d45728_397x441.png&quot;,&quot;is_guest&quot;:false,&quot;bestseller_tier&quot;:10000}],&quot;post_date&quot;:&quot;2022-08-26T00:52:28.730Z&quot;,&quot;cover_image&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0cb804d8-1dd7-4baf-9f7f-985a7de0b881_1600x900.jpeg&quot;,&quot;cover_image_alt&quot;:null,&quot;canonical_url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-elite-overproduction-hypothesis&quot;,&quot;section_name&quot;:null,&quot;id&quot;:70196316,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;newsletter&quot;,&quot;reaction_count&quot;:332,&quot;comment_count&quot;:262,&quot;publication_name&quot;:&quot;Noahpinion&quot;,&quot;publication_logo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F04281755-2cd6-42e5-a496-e69153abebb2_281x281.png&quot;,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true}"></div><p> The basic idea <a class="footnote-anchor" data-component-name="FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id="footnote-anchor-1" href="#footnote-1" target="_self">1</a> is that lots of careers for educated elites — humanities and social science academia, law, journalism, and so on — started becoming a lot scarcer right around the same time. This inevitably led to a bunch of frustrated strivers with big expectations and no way to fulfill them. And that mismatch between expectation and opportunity, I hypothesize, fueled some of the unrest of the 2010s.</p><p> David Austin Walsh appears to be a perfect example of the social process I was describing. He&#39;s had an extremely elite education — he went to the University of Minnesota and did his PhD at Princeton. And he clearly thinks very highly of his own abilities, judging by his plan to write a thread explaining why he was more qualified than every person that ended up getting hired instead of him. One time when he took a practice LSAT and didn&#39;t do well, <a href="https://x.com/Noahpinion/status/1795190992254984630">he blamed his performance</a> on the test questions being “right-wing”.</p><p> That kind of lofty self-regard very easily leads to high expectations for career achievement. And it&#39;s clear that Walsh expected not only to get a tenure-track academic job, but a job in his particular research field — 20th-century US history. There aren&#39;t many such jobs in existence, but that was what Walsh had set his sights on. And it&#39;s his failure to get that specific job, in that specific field, that made him get frustrated and lash out in the thread that made everyone angry.</p><p> It was always very likely that someone was going to get frustrated for exactly this reason. History professorships are an extremely scarce commodity these days. Plenty of people are still getting PhDs in history, but ads for history professor jobs collapsed in the Great Recession and never recovered: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F40647dc0-5361-4e12-ade6-5ff9b4e4fd22_1080x795.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F40647dc0-5361-4e12-ade6-5ff9b4e4fd22_1080x795.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F40647dc0-5361-4e12-ade6-5ff9b4e4fd22_1080x795.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F40647dc0-5361-4e12-ade6-5ff9b4e4fd22_1080x795.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F40647dc0-5361-4e12-ade6-5ff9b4e4fd22_1080x795.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F40647dc0-5361-4e12-ade6-5ff9b4e4fd22_1080x795.jpeg" width="698" height="513.8055555555555" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/40647dc0-5361-4e12-ade6-5ff9b4e4fd22_1080x795.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:795,&quot;width&quot;:1080,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:698,&quot;bytes&quot;:96873,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F40647dc0-5361-4e12-ade6-5ff9b4e4fd22_1080x795.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F40647dc0-5361-4e12-ade6-5ff9b4e4fd22_1080x795.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F40647dc0-5361-4e12-ade6-5ff9b4e4fd22_1080x795.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F40647dc0-5361-4e12-ade6-5ff9b4e4fd22_1080x795.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://theprofessorisin.com/2021/10/04/why-is-it-always-the-historians/">Karen Kelsky</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> And most of the collapse has been <a href="https://theprofessorisin.com/2021/10/04/why-is-it-always-the-historians/">concentrated in jobs for assistant professors</a> — the type of entry-level professor job that Walsh was trying to get.</p><p> Why is no one hiring historians? There are four basic reasons. The first and most important — which almost no one ever talks about, because it&#39;s supposed to be so obvious — is that the US university system is largely done expanding. The 20th century saw a massive build-out of universities, which required hiring a massive number of tenure-track professors. Then it stopped. And because tenure is for life, the departments at the existing universities are clogged with a ton of old profs who will never leave until they age out. New hires must therefore slow to a trickle, since as long as the number of profs is roughly constant, they can only be hired to replace people who retire or die.</p><p> The second reason is the funding crunch that hit universities in the Great Recession of 2008-9. That recession put a lot of pressure on state budgets, and spending on state universities was one thing they could cut. So <a href="https://www.nea.org/nea-today/all-news-articles/state-funding-higher-education-still-lagging">cut they did</a> . And when the economy recovered, some states didn&#39;t restore pre-recession funding levels. Universities made up the lost revenue by hiking tuition, which made everyone mad.</p><p> Those tuition hikes were poorly timed, because of the third reason no one is hiring historians these days: <a href="https://www.statista.com/statistics/236093/higher-education-enrollment-rates-by-age-group-us/">College enrollment itself is falling</a> . This is partly because the number of young people in America has <a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/LFWA24TTUSA647N#">mostly stopped growing</a> . And it&#39;s partly because the financial <em>benefit</em> of higher education — the college wage premium — has <a href="https://files.stlouisfed.org/files/htdocs/publications/review/2019/10/15/is-college-still-worth-it-the-new-calculus-of-falling-returns.pdf">been shrinking</a> slowly since the turn of the century.</p><p> That falling premium is probably a <em>good</em> thing for the country — the likeliest reason is that we sent so many Americans to college that we created a glut of educated workers. But when a country has fewer kids facing higher prices for a less valuable education, you&#39;re probably going to see fewer people go to college. And that means less demand for professors in general.</p><p> But there&#39;s a fourth reason that the demand for historians has fallen: College kids are increasingly avoiding the history major. History degrees peaked as a share of BAs right before the Great Recession, and their share has absolutely collapsed since then: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F47dc398e-6b4f-4dff-94ee-cac5b5ec2fea_1260x764.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F47dc398e-6b4f-4dff-94ee-cac5b5ec2fea_1260x764.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F47dc398e-6b4f-4dff-94ee-cac5b5ec2fea_1260x764.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F47dc398e-6b4f-4dff-94ee-cac5b5ec2fea_1260x764.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F47dc398e-6b4f-4dff-94ee-cac5b5ec2fea_1260x764.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F47dc398e-6b4f-4dff-94ee-cac5b5ec2fea_1260x764.jpeg" width="708" height="429.2952380952381" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/47dc398e-6b4f-4dff-94ee-cac5b5ec2fea_1260x764.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:764,&quot;width&quot;:1260,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:708,&quot;bytes&quot;:177637,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F47dc398e-6b4f-4dff-94ee-cac5b5ec2fea_1260x764.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F47dc398e-6b4f-4dff-94ee-cac5b5ec2fea_1260x764.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F47dc398e-6b4f-4dff-94ee-cac5b5ec2fea_1260x764.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F47dc398e-6b4f-4dff-94ee-cac5b5ec2fea_1260x764.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://benschmidt.org/post/2020-08-25-college-majors-2019-update/">Ben Schmidt</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> In general, students have been flooding out of humanities and non-econ social sciences, and <a href="https://benschmidt.org/post/2020-08-25-college-majors-2019-update/">flooding into fields like computer science</a> that they feel offer them better employment prospects. History has been one of the hardest hit.</p><p> Historians may see research as their primary job, but universities&#39; demand for history professors strongly depends on the number of undergrads majoring in history. If that number is falling off a cliff, you&#39;re just not going to see many tenure-track jobs for historians. Meanwhile, state budget cuts and now falling tuition are promoting the rise of adjuncts and lecturers instead of tenure-track faculty.</p><p> So while half a century ago, tenure-track history jobs were relatively plentiful, today they are incredibly scarce — trying to become a tenured history prof isn&#39;t quite like trying to become a movie star or a drug kingpin, but it has certainly moved in that direction.</p><p> When jobs in a field are scarce, it can exacerbate fights based on identity and representation. When there&#39;s a glut of applicants all vying for one job, the margin between victory and defeat tends to be very narrow. That gives rise to a natural fear that the person who gets picked had some unfair edge. If a White person is picked, nonwhite people may suspect racism;如果选择有色人种，白人可能会怀疑dei的影响。位置越具竞争力，即使是小小的不公平边缘也会使平衡点上的机会越大。</p><p>这符合<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-affirmative-action-had-to-go">我关于美国人如何看待种族和性别歧视的一般理论</a>。在有关大学录取的民意调查中，美国人<a href="https://twitter.com/Noahpinion/status/1486283364747255812">强烈</a><em><a href="https://twitter.com/Noahpinion/status/1486283364747255812">支持</a></em><a href="https://twitter.com/Noahpinion/status/1486283364747255812">“平权行动”</a> ，并<a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2022/10/22/race-college-admissions-poll-results/">强烈</a><em><a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2022/10/22/race-college-admissions-poll-results/">反对</a></em><a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2022/10/22/race-college-admissions-poll-results/">考虑招生的种族</a>。但是这些是同样的事情！可能是美国民意测验的受访者只是不了解他们回答的问题。但是我怀疑这是另外一回事。我认为，美国人喜欢<em>非正式，默认歧视</em>的想法，而不是代表人数不足的群体，但也强烈重视<em>个人公平</em>的观念，因此不喜欢官方的基于规则的歧视。</p><p>这两个目标之间存在自然的张力。当时间好时（当代表性不足的群体的优先提升仍然会使代表性过多的群体做得很好时，甚至很容易忽略这种紧张局势。您可以告诉自己，即使平权行动有偏见或雇用等等，总蛋糕也在增长，因此实际上没有任何团体在总体上<em>受到伤害</em>。增长不堪重负，关注分布。但是，当时代很糟糕，游戏变成零和什至是负面的时，就无法维持这种快乐的心理双重性。因此，争夺种族和性别偏好的斗争再次爆发。</p><p>因此，看到历史领域的种族和性别斗争对我来说是毫不奇怪的。像许多人文科学和非学科的社会科学领域一样，学术史正在萎缩，几乎完全受结构因素的驱动，这些因素似乎很快就会改变。在剩下的东西上的斗争将不可避免地痛苦。</p><p>在我看来，更大的问题是这对我们更广泛的社会产生了什么影响。基本上，精英过度生产理论说，受过教育的精英无法满足的受过教育的精英会通过对更广泛的社会生气和煽动动荡而做出回应。当然，戴维·奥斯汀·沃尔什<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-shouting-class-2-last-refuge">（</a> David Austin Walsh）作为一种敏锐的社交媒体的有争议的职业适合预测T。坦率地说，这对美国来说不是很好。</p><p>那么，我们如何与精英生产斗争？显而易见的方法是为受过教育的精英提供更多的职业，但这对整个社会来说可能会非常昂贵。像沃尔什（Walsh）这样的人们对自己的职业生涯具有非常狭窄，具体的期望，并且满足所有这些期望，所有这些人都需要将我们最有才华的个人纳入本质上是工作工作的工作。我们无力付钱给所有人成为他们选择的人文或社会科学领域的终身教授。</p><p>相反，我认为问题需要<em>改变期望</em>。我认为，巨大的衰退和库维德在这里确实有所帮助，因为他们的一生将是通往繁荣，名望和尊重的人的生活。因此，那里有些重置。最重要的是，我们可能应该在诸如学术工作稀缺的历史和私营部门职业的历史等领域中获得更少的博士学位。</p><p> （当然，美国父母可能应该停止告诉孩子他们是世界上最聪明的孩子，他们注定要出于伟大等。 .)</p><p>但是，除此之外，我认为学术顾问和其他有影响力的人物也应该使受过教育的人们的期望更加<em>模糊</em>。 “我将成为一所良好大学的20世纪美国历史领域的终身教授”，这是一个非常特定的期望，很难满足。 “我将要做一项不错的工作，从而做一些有趣的事情，同时也许在旁边写一本书”是一个非常模糊的期望，对于几乎所有美国的博士学位持有者来说都是可以实现的。美国街道需要学会去生命的景点带走它们。从我这里拿走它 - 这样更有趣。 </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,