d,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2c663799-8d26-4456-8c14-8283b618f705_590x590.png" loading="lazy"><span class="embedded-post-publication-name">建筑物理学</span></div><div class="embedded-post-title-wrapper"><div class="embedded-post-title">如何在五年内建造300,000架飞机</div></div><div class="embedded-post-body">盟军在美国巨大的工业产出中赢得了第二次世界大战的胜利，这已经不是什么秘密了。甚至在美国发动战争之前，美国人为盟友提供了数亿美元的设备，并在1938年至1943年之间。</div><div class="embedded-post-cta-wrapper"><span class="embedded-post-cta">阅读更多</span></div><div class="embedded-post-meta">12天前·148喜欢·36条评论·Brian Potter</div></div><p>令人惊讶的是，美国几乎从头开始拍打这个行业：</p><blockquote><p> 1937年，美国生产了约3,100架飞机，其中大多数是小型私人飞机。战争之前，美国制造的飞机价值约为生产罐的价值的四分之一，只有3.5％的汽车价值……</p><p>赢得战争所需的飞机需要对飞机行业进行完整的转变。在1939年至1944年之间……飞机的总重量增加了64倍。1940年，机身行业只雇用了59,000人；三年后达到939,000，另外还有339,000架建筑飞机发动机……[b]战争飞机发动机工厂地板空间的尽头从170万平方英尺增加到7500万平方英尺，一家大型发动机工厂的空间比以前更多由整个战前发动机行业使用。</p></blockquote><p>美国如何完成这一令人难以置信的工业壮举？波特确定了几个关键因素。</p><p>首先是<strong>需求的稳定来源</strong>。需求来自英国和法国，该法国下令战机与纳粹作战，就在第二次世界大战之前和战争初期。可预测的需求使美国制造商能够采取必要的巨大风险，以扩大巨大倍数扩大其工厂。涉及现金还帮助美国飞机公司直接为这一扩展提供了资金。</p><p>另一个因素是<strong>大量融资</strong>，其中大部分来自国防工厂公司，基本上是一家大型国有银行，为国防生产提供了资金。提出DPC想法的人是通用汽车的前高管Bill Knudsen。克努森的照片位于这篇文章的顶部，他是出色的历史书<em><a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/book-review-freedoms-forge">《自由锻造》</a></em>的主角。重要的是，诺德森和他在罗斯福政府中的雇主具有远见卓识，知道一场重大战争即将来临，并在炸弹开始坠落<em>之前，</em>将美国制造业扩大了大量。</p><p>第三个因素是<strong>现有的工业能力</strong>。美国有大量的工厂建造汽车，电器等，其中许多很快被重新用于飞机和飞机发动机制造。美国还拥有许多“初级工业”  - 铝冶炼厂等，这些工业能够为飞机行业提供所需的所有原材料。</p><p>第四个因素是<strong>妇女</strong>，她们满足了大量飞机工厂的劳动力需求的40％。著名的铆钉罗西（Rosie The Riveter）是基于这些工人的。</p><p>在帖子的结尾，波特揭示了他认为现代美国可以从惊人的WW2飞机生产工作中学到的课程：</p><blockquote><p> [t]他的成功是高度偶然的。美国没有做好准备扩大飞机行业的准备……政府和行业都没有组织基础设施来处理规模，或者制定规模的计划……直到1942年，德国入侵波兰和法国三年了英国宣布对德国的回应战争，美国飞机的生产确实加剧了，这甚至是由于英国和法国的巨大早期命令，以及像比尔·诺德森（Bill Knudsen）这样的遥远的人的工作，他们知道需要多长时间扩大制造业务…</p><p>第二次世界大战飞机的生产表明，复杂的制造业有可能迅速发展。但这也显示了扩大规模的局限性；即使在紧急情况下，有些事情也只能加速太多，成功取决于事先做出的准备。</p></blockquote><p>对于美国当前的情况来说，这显然非常重要。我们<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/americans-are-still-not-worried-enough">甚至对与中国的冲突不太担心</a>，因此，我们并没有做任何类似于投资的东西，也不是为了资助国防工业规模的规模而进行的监管变更。乌克兰和台湾的命令<em>可能</em>会为美国国防工业振兴自身的稳定需求，但我们的政府与必要的资金不一致。</p><p>我担心，唯一学习美国第二次世界大战的经验教训的国家是中国。</p><h4> 2.美国是否有新的两党“新生者”共识？</h4><p>大卫·莱昂哈特（David Leonhardt）在《纽约时报》上有<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/05/19/briefing/centrism-washington-neopopulism.html">一篇出色的文章</a>，汇集了如今美国政府正在发生的两个重要主题：</p><ol><li><p>两党合作的安静增加（马特·伊格利亚斯称之为“<a href="https://www.slowboring.com/p/the-rise-and-importance-of-secret">秘密国会</a>”）</p></li><li><p>经济思维从新自由主义向工业主义的转变</p></li></ol><p>莱昂哈特（Leonhardt） - 我认为正确地确定了这一转变背后的两个因素：</p><ol><li><p>中国领导的威权力量集团的兴起，其权力竞争或超过美国的权力</p></li><li><p>数十年新自由主义政策似乎失败了，以帮助工人阶级</p></li></ol><p>这里有一些摘录：</p><blockquote><p>中心主义的概念是许多进步主义者和保守派的厌恶，使人联想到糊状的节制。但是新的中间主义并不总是那么温和。强迫出售流行的社交应用并不完全胆怯，也不面对中国和俄罗斯。重建美国基础设施和加强国内半导体行业的法案是雄心勃勃的经济政策……</p><p>新的中心主义……是新自由主义未能实现的认识，取而代之的是新的世界观。称其为肿瘤……</p><p>其他哪些新毒剂政策可能还存在？有可能解决中国崛起的更多立法，并且可以实现更多的工业政策。一项法案，以确保美国能够获得锂和铜等关键矿物质，这两者都有资格……帮助年轻家庭的政策也是合理的……</p><p>几十年来，华盛顿采取了一系列政策，许多选民不喜欢这些政策，而这些政策<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/10/24/briefing/the-american-dream.html">并没有接近</a>他们承诺的结果。可以理解的是，许多公民变得沮丧。这种挫败感导致了一种新昆虫主义的轰动，该灾害试图振兴美国经济并与该国的全球竞争对手竞争。与该国的两极分化一样，其两个政党至少正在努力对这种现实做出回应，他们发现了意外的共同点。</p></blockquote><p>我认为这是一个非常敏锐和及时的文章。我认为“新昆虫主义”一词不会持续下去，主要是因为“民粹主义”一词的负面含义。但是我也认为，“民粹主义”并不是这里发生的事情的正确框架。一般而言，美国人<a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2024/05/01/americans-remain-critical-of-china/">对中国有负面看法</a>，但是为了真正阻止和平衡中国的许多实际政策步骤（例如出口控制，半导体补贴，扩大联盟等）实际上是精英项目，而不是试图取悦的项目选民。</p><p>同时，由于确切的原因，如果他们引起公众的注意，他们将激活双方基地的党派精力，使合理的妥协妥善妥协，这是一个确切的原因，这是静静地完成的，例如<a href="https://www.democracydocket.com/news-alerts/biden-signs-electoral-count-reform-act-into-law/">选举伯爵改革</a>，例如选举伯爵改革，例如选举伯爵改革，从而使合理的妥协妥善妥协更难。伊格莱西亚斯（Yglesias）称其为“秘密国会”是有原因的 - 全国大部分地区仍然处于痛苦，脆弱的情绪，民粹主义的能量通常仍在将国会推向划分，僵局和顽固性。</p><p>尽管如此，我确实认为莱昂哈特的文章抓住了许多关于美国治理现在所在的重要事实。美国的主要挑战已从内部的文化，身份和经济分配转变为外部威胁，美国领导人的一部分和美国人民正在慢慢唤醒这一事实。我也同意他的评估，即未来的两党计划可能包括更多的工业政策，更多与安全有关的政策以及帮助儿童的政策。</p><p>我还认为他错过了另一个大型住房政策。高租金仍在全国范围内引起广泛的不满，为了打击不可避免的房屋建造的当地障碍和限制，需要采取政府行动。有一些非常令人鼓舞的迹象表明，在未来几年中，住房丰度可能是两党合作的重点，例如，<a href="https://www.housingfinance.com/policy-legislation/yimby-act-passes-house_o">刚刚通过</a>众议院的<a href="https://www.semafor.com/article/05/23/2024/is-congress-having-its-yimby-moment">Yimby法案</a>。</p><h4> 3.假科学似乎正在上升</h4><p>每个人都知道科学的复制危机。现在是时候应对欺诈危机了。</p><p>最近，我看到了许多有关伪造的研究结果的令人不安的故事。 <a href="https://www.npr.org/2023/07/27/1190568472/dan-ariely-francesca-gino-harvard-dishonesty-fabricated-data">诚实的研究人员</a>伪造了他们的数据，阿尔茨海默氏症的<a href="https://www.npr.org/2023/07/19/1188828810/stanford-university-president-resigns">神经科学伪造丑闻</a>迫使斯坦福大学总统下台，以及<a href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/nature-retracts-controversial-room-temperature-superconductor-study/">室温的超导体</a>研究也被假冒了。但是这些似乎只是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/science/data-colada-debunk-stanford-president-research-14664f3">冰山一角</a>：</p><blockquote><p>每年的撤回数量反映了给定年份发表的论文的十分之一，换句话说，其中一个是1,000个。然而，该数字已从2000年的大约40次撤回率中显着增长，这超过了发表论文的年度增长。</p><p>近年来，取回急剧急剧上升，主要有两个原因：首先，侦查，主要是由志愿者<a href="https://retractionwatch.com/2018/06/17/meet-the-scientific-sleuths-ten-whove-had-an-impact-on-the-scientific-literature/">梳理</a>学术文学的异常，其次，第二大出版商（迟来）认识到他们的<a href="https://retractionwatch.com/2023/03/09/wiley-paused-hindawi-special-issues-amid-quality-problems-lost-9-million-in-revenue/">商业模式</a>使他们对<a href="https://retractionwatch.com/2021/12/20/revealed-the-inner-workings-of-a-paper-mill/">造纸厂</a>敏感 - 科学厂 -切碎的商店出售从作者身份到整个手稿再到需要出版的研究人员，以免他们灭亡。</p></blockquote><p>现在有证据表明已经伪造了<a href="https://www.science.org/content/article/hundreds-cancer-papers-mention-cell-lines-don-t-seem-exist?utm_medium=ownedSocial&amp;utm_source=Twitter&amp;utm_campaign=NewsfromScience">大量的癌症研究</a>：</p><blockquote><p>研究完整性侦探可能已经找到了一个新的危险信号，以识别欺诈性论文，至少在癌症研究中：关于人类细胞系的发现显然不存在。这是最近一项研究的结论，该研究调查了八种细胞系，这些细胞系在2004年至2023年发表的420篇论文中始终拼错，包括在癌症研究中排名较高的期刊中。其中一些拼写错误可能是无意的错误，但是235篇论文的子集提供了有关八条线中七个的细节，这些<a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/pdf/10.1002/ijc.34995">细节表明实际上没有进行过的实验</a>，侦探说……这些论文可能是冰山一角， [作者詹妮弗]伯恩说。自2023年1月以来，已经发表了有关人类癌细胞系的50,000多种学术文章。伯恩（Byrne）的团队总共确定了23条拼错线，但将其分析限制在420篇论文中提到的8个，以使工作负载易于管理。</p></blockquote><p>现在发现大量伪造的生物研究正在从字面上<a href="https://www.abc.net.au/news/2024-05-21/wiley-hindawi-articles-scandal-broader-crisis-trust-universities/103868662">停止出版</a>一些学术期刊：</p><blockquote><p>去年，威利（Wiley）发生了一件奇怪的事情。医学研究…到11月，威利（Wiley）撤回了多达8,000篇论文， <a href="https://www.science.org/content/article/paper-mills-bribing-editors-scholarly-journals-science-investigation-finds">告诉科学</a>“已经确定了我们的投资组合中的数百名不良演员”……一个月后，该公司在精致的公司中<a href="https://s27.q4cdn.com/812717746/files/doc_financials/2024/q2/Q224-Earnings-Presentation-Final.pdf">宣布</a>：“ Wiley日落了Hindawi品牌”。</p></blockquote><p>作为企业，科学取决于信任。科学家既没有时间，也没有手段来检查他们所引用和建立工作的每个研究人员的每个结果。当大量的研究人员彻底欺诈时，整个系统都处于危险之中，因为在某个时候，没有人可以信任别人的结果。如果您担心那些巨人可能是虚幻的，那么您就无法站在巨人的肩膀上。</p><p>然而，现代科学的激励措施似乎几乎是为了鼓励广泛的欺诈。科学成功的关键指标是1）同行评审期刊的出版物，以及2）这些出版物的引用。正如<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodhart%27s_law">古德哈特（Goodhart）的法律</a>告诉我们的那样，所有指标最终都将被授予。可以通过多种方法来播放发布或渗透系统 -  P黑客式，规格搜索，<a href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w32468">引用环</a>等。欺诈可能不是最简单或最安全的。但这几乎可以肯定是最具破坏性的。</p><p>同行评审是对欺诈的辩护。即使是谨慎，勤奋的审稿人，他们可能会发现不良统计或薄弱的推论，也将难以确定完全的伪造。这留下了文化，这是对科学体系的完整性的普遍自豪感 - 作为对欺诈的一线防御。从来没有任何保证，这种文化将保持完整，因为越来越多的钱被科学投入。</p><p>这表明，为了维持科学的企业，需要更多的“欺诈警察”才能抓住不法行为者。但这也应该提出一个问题，即是否应大量发表研究人员。奖励质量而不是数量可能会更好。</p><h4> 4.渴望修改的安静崛起</h4><p>什么是最终技术？在许多经典的科幻故事中，它<em>比光线更快</em>，这将使我们能够探索甚至殖民无限的新世界。在其他情况下，它是<em>个性上传</em>，这将使我们能够创建数字世界以适应我们所有的欲望。在其他人中，它是<em>人工通用情报</em>，它足够聪明，可以给我们任何我们想要的东西。</p><p>但是，一些故事的故事具有一个甚至陌生人的想法，可能会胜过上述所有内容：<em>欲望修改</em>，这将使我们能够改变基本的心理学。当我们可以改变自己以更适合已经拥有的世界时，探索或创造新世界的意义是什么？</p><p>人类一直在试图通过冥想之类的东西来改变我们数千年的欲望。最近，我们在混合物中添加了药物 - 抗抑郁药，抗焦虑药等。我们甚至尝试了<a href="https://www.amazon.com/Pleasure-Shock-Stimulation-Forgotten-Inventor/dp/1101986530">深脑刺激</a>以缓解严重的抑郁症。</p><p>现在，我们正在发现以新的且越来越多的方式改变我们的欲望的药物。研究人员发现，像Ozempic这样的GLP-1药物抑制食欲并能够减轻体重，实际上以<a href="https://newatlas.com/medical/novo-nordisk-ozempic-weight-loss/">多种有趣的方式</a>改变了人类的欲望：</p><blockquote><p>根据丹麦研究人员的说法，目前的突破性减肥药只是开始的，该研究人员努力针对大脑自然可塑性的新治疗方法，这可能会抵消不良的副作用并提供更长期的益处……</p><p>当前GLP-1药物模仿进食后天然激素反应，发出“饱腹感”并减慢胃的排空，而新治疗方法则使用GLP-1肽在血脑屏障上“走私”分子，并进入食欲中控制中心…[T]他的新方法可以利用大脑的可塑性来巩固其食欲中心的新途径 - 在治疗停止后很长时间将保持原样。</p></blockquote><p>而且也有迹象表明，这些药物有助于消除<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/search/research-news/19361/">对酒精和其他成瘾性药物的渴望</a>。想象一下，瘾君子是否只能服用药丸就可以恢复！</p><p>同时，药物只是欲望修改的开始。如果药物是一种钝器，则<a href="https://www.neuromodulation.com/about-neuromodulation">神经调节</a>（直接干扰大脑的电路）可能会成为细腻的手术刀。 Neuralink是最著名的新大脑植入器设备，已经 <a href="https://www.wired.com/story/neuralink-first-patient-interview-noland-arbaugh-elon-musk/">取得了有趣的结果</a>，它只是当前正在测试的许多设备和方法之一。</p><p>也许最终的技术成就将是破解人性本身。</p><h4> 5.人们正在建设性地思考放松管制</h4><p>我总是说，放松管制太重要了，无法留给放松者。</p><p>好吧，我真的不总是这样说，但是我计划现在开始。基本上，几十年来，我们美国人拥有一堆自由主义者，新自由主义者，自由营销人员，自由主义者，无论您想称呼他们如何 - 告诉我们，唯一的好法规是废除的法规。每个法规<em>所做的</em>确切所做的是次要利益 - 取消调节器将根据联邦登记册中的页数或其他此类批量措施来衡量法规。</p><p>这种方法不是很有帮助的，因为从本质上讲，没有政治家愿意不加选择地缩小联邦登记册。当研究人员开始<a href="https://marginalrevolution.com/marginalrevolution/2018/02/federal-regulation-not-cause-declining-dynamism.html">研究这个想法</a>时，他们发现法规量的数量是微观经济结果的非常差的预测指标。</p><p>那么，这是否意味着法规是良性的，我们应该不理会吗？恰恰相反。这只是意味着“监管”是一个伞术语，它涵盖了某些概括的政策类别，无法简单地是好事或简单的坏事。取而代之的是，我们需要深入研究法规的细节，以找出哪些帮助以及哪些损害。</p><p>幸运的是，这些天我看到很多聪明的人在做到这一点。例如， <a href="https://www.niskanencenter.org/addressing-medicare-spending-and-hospital-consolidation-with-site-neutral-payments/">这是Niskanen中心关于Medicare的基于现场计费的报告</a>，认为这会导致政府过分支付医疗服务，并加剧了医疗保健领域的垄断权，同时并没有改善患者的健康状况。</p><p>第二个例子是亚历山大·考夫曼（Alexander Kaufman）的<a href="https://www.volts.wtf/p/the-obscure-but-extremely-important">十字军东征，以改善建筑法规</a>。关于建筑物如何建造的规则可能会对能源效率产生巨大影响，但是美国建筑法规高度分散且过时。</p><p>第三个例子是<a href="https://www.commerce.gov/sites/default/files/streamlining_permitting_and_reducing_regulatory_burdens_for_domestic_manufacturing.pdf">该商务部的报告，</a>介绍了如何改善制造业的许可和其他监管负担。如果美国要恢复其工业基础，这显然非常重要。 Commerce要求大量的制造商和与制造业相关的公司告诉他们最繁重的法规。他们确定了大约二十组规则最繁重的规则。其中大多数是环境规则，其中许多与许可有关。下一个任务是审查这些规则，并询问如何保护环境，同时仍然能够快速，便宜地建造许多工厂。</p><p> <a href="https://americanaffairsjournal.org/2023/11/its-not-just-nepa-reforming-environmental-permitting/">托马斯·霍克曼（Thomas Hochman）在美国事务中的一篇文章</a>支持了这一总体想法，认为《清洁空气法》是匆忙而艰难地写的，并且该法案的明智之举将能够保护空气质量，同时不阻止工厂，发电厂或住房。</p><p>这些都是伟大的努力，它们只是对那里发生的事情的味道。考虑如何改善美国的监管，而不是将其削减，而是在必要时减少它，在适当的情况下将其降低，甚至在需要时将新法规添加新法规，这确实是一种复兴。这是一个非常令人兴奋的智力发酵领域，也是巨大的政策分析的机会。这也可能对我们国家的未来至关重要。 </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-f84?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-f84?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><p></p><p></p>; 
A pivotal moment for Japan's national defenseA guest post by Jonathan Grady https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/a-pivotal-moment-for-japans-national https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/a-pivotal-moment-for-japans-nationalNoah Smith Sun, 26 May 2024 02:47:34 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg" width="1090" height="727" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:727,&quot;width&quot;:1090,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:51965,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1c6f1065-ddc9-40ed-be2f-9af4c706ba6d_1090x727.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源： <a href="https://www.defense.gov/Multimedia/Photos/igphoto/2002963956/">USMC</a></figcaption></figure></div><p><em>我一直在写很多关于<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/americans-are-still-not-worried-enough">亚洲重大战争的威胁的文章</a>，但我在这个方程式中的作用并不多。然而，日本将处于这场战争的中心。中国对台湾的扣押将使<a href="https://thediplomat.com/2024/05/yes-japan-will-defend-taiwan/">日本的安全处于严重的危险之中</a>。这是中国PLA官员<a href="https://globaltaiwan.org/2020/12/fortnightly-review-v-5-issue-24/">培训手册</a>的翻译报价：</em></p><blockquote><p><em>一旦台湾与中国大陆统一，日本的海上交流将完全属于中国战斗机和轰炸机的惊人范围……日本的经济活动和战争潜力基本上将被摧毁……封锁会导致海上发货减少，并且可以减少，并且可以减少，并且可以减少，并且可以减少。甚至在日本岛上造成饥荒。</em></p></blockquote><p><em>中国驻日本大使<a href="https://x.com/Joel_P_Atkinson/status/1793424845356839304">最近表示</a>：“一旦日本的国家与坦克与中国分裂的坦克相关，日本人民将被带入大火。”</em></p><p><em>鉴于极端的危险，日本的国防政策似乎极为重要。我建议该国应该<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/japan-and-south-korea-need-nuclear">部署核武器</a>，但是该国领导人在传统的军事能力方面可能还有很多其他事情。</em></p><p><em>一个有很多想法的人是咨询公司<a href="https://www.canarygroupllc.com/">Canary Group</a>的创始校长<a href="https://x.com/_JonathanGrady">乔纳森·格雷迪（Jonathan Grady）</a> ，他已经对<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?app=desktop&amp;v=7sTDJzc76rU">四轮人在亚洲安全中的作用</a>进行了<a href="https://www.cnbc.com/quad-summit-and-china-game-theory-predictions-for-the-future-of-the-quad/">战略性分析</a>，有时也对<a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Opinion/To-pay-for-defense-buildup-Kishida-must-act-swiftly-on-taxes">日本国防政策</a>进行了撰写。他在这篇来宾帖子中解释说，日本将不得不克服一些经济和政治障碍，以继续其国防积累并确保其自身的安全。</em></p><div><hr></div><h4>日本必须很快决定重大防御</h4><p>日本站在一个关键时刻，面临着关于其国防战略的紧急决定。日本有了显着提高其国防能力的地位，将其国防预算提高了60％，以提高对印度太平洋安全的影响。这种支出的激增旨在增强东京对中国的威慑并促进区域和平。但是，雄心勃勃的计划受到领导犹豫不决的危害，这是一种复杂的政治格局和严重的财务限制，威胁到这一历史性的建筑。随着赌注高 - 在与政治生存相冲突的同时，塑造了跨首都的威慑计划 - 决策结果很重要。由于日本面临选举年，缺乏政治决心和明确的资金机制迫使真诚的行动来确定其国防野心的未来范围和融资。这些选择将定义日本是否意识到其全部防御潜力或面临重大妥协。</p><h4><strong>加强日本的防御姿势</strong></h4><p>历史悠久的第二次世界大战后建立旨在增强东京对印度太平洋地区中国侵略的威慑，这是对全球安全至关重要的地区。此外，它构成了一项更广泛的国际战略的一部分，以在中国的竞争领土上保持和平地位。日本独特的岛屿地理和美国基地在土壤上的脆弱性强调了这些计划的紧迫性。值得注意的是，日本拥有<a href="https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/japan-now-has-mini-aircraft-carriers-carrying-f-35-fighters-209792">全球第二大</a>的F-35战斗机飞机，并正在购买<a href="https://apnews.com/article/japan-us-tomahawk-missile-defense-0bcabfc4a87bf1a16beceec1b0c426fb">数百枚战斧巡航导弹</a>，使东京反击能力能够抵抗敌人基地，并增强其防御和美国基地和部队的安全。 </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg" width="781" height="521" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:521,&quot;width&quot;:781,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:100485,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7a3f44e8-a898-4411-872d-2280905e99d0_781x521.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源：<a href="https://www.af.mil/News/Photos/igphoto/2002917867/">美国空军</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>但是，对日本的政治决心和支持增加支出的财务能力的怀疑造成了高风险的困境。东京可能无法实现其先前计划的一些防御能力。即使日本要确保其大多数愿望列表项目，但可能有限的弹药储备会限制预算，也会阻碍东京一些新发现的国防能力。由于它们与潜在的冲突非常接近， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/war-game-finds-u-s-taiwan-can-defend-against-a-chinese-invasion-11660047804">日本的美国基地是目标</a>。日本缺乏以前计划的能力是对这些基地和士兵的损害。日本政府必须很快解决其国防支出的困境，因为国防预算资金及其安全含义的适当压力。 </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F668ea3d4-41aa-42c1-89f7-cf26ebc3aead_975x648.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F668ea3d4-41aa-42c1-89f7-cf26ebc3aead_975x648.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F668ea3d4-41aa-42c1-89f7-cf26ebc3aead_975x648.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F668ea3d4-41aa-42c1-89f7-cf26ebc3aead_975x648.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F668ea3d4-41aa-42c1-89f7-cf26ebc3aead_975x648.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F668ea3d4-41aa-42c1-89f7-cf26ebc3aead_975x648.jpeg" width="975" height="648" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/668ea3d4-41aa-42c1-89f7-cf26ebc3aead_975x648.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:648,&quot;width&quot;:975,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:124975,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F668ea3d4-41aa-42c1-89f7-cf26ebc3aead_975x648.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F668ea3d4-41aa-42c1-89f7-cf26ebc3aead_975x648.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F668ea3d4-41aa-42c1-89f7-cf26ebc3aead_975x648.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F668ea3d4-41aa-42c1-89f7-cf26ebc3aead_975x648.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">阿利·伯克（Arleigh Burke）阶级导致的驱逐舰巴里（USS Barry）发射了战斧巡航导弹；资料来源：美国海军</figcaption></figure></div><h4><strong>资金挑战和政治优柔寡断</strong></h4><p>尽管日本的国防野心很明确，但实现它们的途径充满了财务和政治挑战。日本在资助其飙升预算方面的犹豫不决破坏了其积累努力。缺乏对资金的明确性使建筑物在充满挑战的政治环境中脆弱。随着资金计划的几次延误，随着时间的流逝，日本政府面临越来越不利的政治局势。</p><p>作为日本新的<a href="https://www.mod.go.jp/j/policy/agenda/guideline/pdf/security_strategy_en.pdf">国家安全战略</a>的一部分，去年日本政府预留了五年的国防预算的43万亿日元（约3000亿美元），比以前的国防支出增加了60％。扩大的国防预算旨在帮助增强对中国和朝鲜的威慑，并为东京提供反击能力。</p><p>尽管国防政策在日本公众中很受欢迎，但为此付出的手段不是。这导致了如何在过去两年中充分资助支出增加的慢性犹豫不决。预算包括税收加息的一万亿日元（约73亿美元）旨在帮助资助增加，将<a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/asia-pacific/japan-implement-defence-taxation-appropriate-time-2024-draft-2022-12-16/">在“ 2024年或之后的适当时间”</a>实施。这种优柔寡断的语言是在扩大国防预算的同时延迟不受欢迎的税收加息的妥协。不幸的是，日本政府多次将徒步旅行推迟了几次，现在<a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Defense/Japan-likely-to-put-off-raising-taxes-to-build-up-defense-until-2026">将税收加息至2026年</a>。 The ruling Liberal Democratic Party government asserts <em>it will respect the planned defense increases</em> , <em><a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Defense/Japan-likely-to-put-off-raising-taxes-to-build-up-defense-until-2026">if the tax hikes are implemented by 2026</a></em> . This further ambiguity raises concerns whether defense priorities will be fully funded or continue to be funded, and undermines the Japanese government&#39;s credibility.</p><p> Compounding its indecision, the government flirted with calling an election for nearly a year. During the past summer, speculation peaked that the government would call an election to lock in electoral gains, as it was enjoying <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-05-01/support-for-japan-pm-tops-50-amid-speculation-on-early-election">a spike in polls surpassing 50% in approval</a> following foreign policy victories.</p><p> Unfortunately, the government did not call an election after months of consideration. The Kishida government <a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Japan-PM-Kishida-s-approval-rating-hits-new-low-Nikkei-poll">approval polls then precipitously dropped</a> , even before an unprecedented corruption scandal was publicly known. The Japanese government missed its best opportunity to call an election when it was at a point of strength, subsequently missing a major opportunity to secure its coveted defense funding. As highlighted by the <a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Japan-PM-Kishida-s-approval-rating-hits-new-low-Nikkei-poll">Nikkei Asia graph</a> , the Kishida government missed its optimal opportunity before the corruption scandal. </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1789dc1c-1771-4543-ba3a-514c195c80e4_870x491.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1789dc1c-1771-4543-ba3a-514c195c80e4_870x491.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1789dc1c-1771-4543-ba3a-514c195c80e4_870x491.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1789dc1c-1771-4543-ba3a-514c195c80e4_870x491.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1789dc1c-1771-4543-ba3a-514c195c80e4_870x491.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1789dc1c-1771-4543-ba3a-514c195c80e4_870x491.jpeg" width="870" height="491" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1789dc1c-1771-4543-ba3a-514c195c80e4_870x491.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:491,&quot;width&quot;:870,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:96437,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1789dc1c-1771-4543-ba3a-514c195c80e4_870x491.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1789dc1c-1771-4543-ba3a-514c195c80e4_870x491.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1789dc1c-1771-4543-ba3a-514c195c80e4_870x491.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1789dc1c-1771-4543-ba3a-514c195c80e4_870x491.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Japan-PM-Kishida-s-approval-rating-hits-new-low-Nikkei-poll">Nikkei Asia</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> The indecision does not come as a surprise. In an analysis earlier this past year in Nikkei Asia, I indicated that <a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Opinion/To-pay-for-defense-buildup-Kishida-must-act-swiftly-on-taxes">the Japanese government needed to move fast</a> on passing its tax hikes. If it did not pass the tax hikes quickly enough, it risked pulling back again on its tax hike timeline. I further indicated if enough time was allowed to pass, a coalition that included some of the inner circle members from the current government would resist the unpopular tax hikes. I indicated these individuals would adopt a politically motivated indifference. Since that time, Prime Minister Kishida announced <a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Kishida-takes-charge-of-foreign-policy-with-Kamikawa-pick">abrupt cabinet changes</a> , unsuccessfully shifting public opinion. Some of these inner circle members were seen as insufficiently loyal to the Prime Minister.</p><p> Significant political constraints compound the Japanese government&#39;s indecision. The Japanese government severely wounded itself with a recent unprecedented political scandal; former Prime Minister Shinzo Abe&#39;s faction, the largest faction in the Japanese government, was <a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Japan-s-political-fundraising-scandals-4-things-to-know">running a secret slush fund</a> . The scheme implicated senior lawmakers, leading to resignations from the Prime Minister&#39;s cabinet. The unprecedented scandal has created an unsettling backdrop and dealt a <a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Japan-political-funds-scandal-deals-blow-to-Kishida-s-agenda">major blow for the Prime Minister&#39;s agenda</a> , with the unpopular tax hikes postponed and a nosedive in polls while he scrambles for political survival.</p><p> Government polling is now historically bad. A recent poll found approval for the Prime Minister&#39;s cabinet dropped to <a href="https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2024/04/11/japan/politics/japan-kishida-cabinet-support-fresh-low/">16.6%, the worst polling in over 10 years</a> since the Prime Minister&#39;s Liberal Democratic Party came to power in 2012. Another poll found a <a href="https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20240520/p2a/00m/0na/004000c">disapproval rate of 74%</a> for the Prime Minister&#39;s cabinet, among the worst polling <a href="https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20231218/p2a/00m/0na/003000c">in over 75 years</a> since recording began in 1947. A Nikkei poll found a<a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Kishida-cabinet-s-disapproval-rating-reaches-record-high">record high 69% disapproval</a> of the Prime Minister&#39;s cabinet since he came to office.</p><p> Unsurprisingly, unpopular tax hikes – even if meant for critical national defense spending – have been pushed aside at a time of historically unpopular polling. However, indecision over funding the spending increases persisted long before the drop in polls, detrimentally affecting Japan&#39;s defense plans. Indecision also cost its leaders a significant opportunity to lock in its gains. Japan will need to find a way to pay for the defense spending increases. To address these funding challenges, the government has explored strategies related to asset sales, including a <a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Japan-weighs-selling-rest-of-NTT-stake-for-defense-funding">sale of government shares</a> in NTT, a major Japanese telco. If Japan cannot fund its own defense buildup, the government&#39;s prolonged indecision will damage planned defense capabilities and potentially its own credibility.</p><h4> <strong>Economic hurdles in defense spending</strong></h4><p> Financial constraints further complicate Japan&#39;s defense ambitions. Significant debt levels and the recent currency devaluation directly impact its ability to procure advanced defense systems, potentially compromising strategic initiatives. Raising debt to finance spending, a common practice in the past, now raises concerns due to Japan&#39;s already substantial debt. There are concerns that Japan&#39;s significant debt levels are now too high and could undermine the Japanese economy. Japan already carries substantial debt, prompting warnings from some economists.</p><p> A prominent Japanese economist, responding to proposals for debt to fund the defense buildup, described a debt proposal as <a href="https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/japan-must-finance-its-military-buildup-by-raising-taxes-by-takatoshi-ito-2023-01">“unsustainable.”</a> According to the NYU Stern Volatility Lab, when normalized for GDP Japan has faraway the <a href="https://vlab.stern.nyu.edu/srisk">largest amount of financial systemic risk</a> from its debt among developed financial markets. In the event of a financial crisis, Japan&#39;s systemic risk amounts to over 17% of its GDP. As illustrated below, Japan leads systemic risk among developed financial markets, highlighting economic vulnerabilities </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F118ed380-1e2d-44d5-aa87-be356d2e980a_975x399.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F118ed380-1e2d-44d5-aa87-be356d2e980a_975x399.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F118ed380-1e2d-44d5-aa87-be356d2e980a_975x399.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F118ed380-1e2d-44d5-aa87-be356d2e980a_975x399.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F118ed380-1e2d-44d5-aa87-be356d2e980a_975x399.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F118ed380-1e2d-44d5-aa87-be356d2e980a_975x399.jpeg" width="975" height="399" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/118ed380-1e2d-44d5-aa87-be356d2e980a_975x399.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:399,&quot;width&quot;:975,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:68576,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F118ed380-1e2d-44d5-aa87-be356d2e980a_975x399.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F118ed380-1e2d-44d5-aa87-be356d2e980a_975x399.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F118ed380-1e2d-44d5-aa87-be356d2e980a_975x399.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F118ed380-1e2d-44d5-aa87-be356d2e980a_975x399.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://vlab.stern.nyu.edu/srisk">NYU Stern V-Lab</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> In the event of a financial crisis, Japanese banks risk a capital shortfall that would be highly damaging. If the Japanese yield curve were to surge, then the financial sector – mostly its banks – that own a large chunk of the Japanese sovereign debt will have collateral damage due to value losses. Japan is also a graying nation with <a href="https://www.mof.go.jp/english/policy/budget/budget/fy2024/01.pdf">over half its budget</a> dedicated to social spending and debt servicing. Additional debt raises can further weigh against the government&#39;s budget and create a more <a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Economy/Japan-debt-servicing-costs-face-climb-as-BOJ-ends-negative-rates">challenging financial situation</a> for the Japanese government.</p><p> Compounding financial challenges, the recent drop in Japanese currency has reduced Japan&#39;s buying power for defense acquisitions. The then-$300 Billion five year budget set in December 2022 questionably <a href="https://www.reuters.com/markets/currencies/weak-yen-forces-japan-shrink-historic-military-spending-plan-2023-11-03/">assumed a 108 yen to dollar exchange rate</a> . However, the rate at the time was approximately 130 yen to the dollar; at the time, the lower 108 rate had not been seen in over a year since 2021. The exchange rate subsequently surged to over 150 yen to the dollar, further <a href="https://thediplomat.com/2024/03/will-japans-defense-spending-hike-be-enough/">diminishing Japan&#39;s buying power</a> for major defense acquisitions.</p><p> Japan has already cut back some of its purchases of military aircraft, but it is yet to be seen whether further cuts will occur. The depreciating currency also reduces the buying power of the unpopular tax hikes meant to pay for defense. To continue with planned purchases, Japan will need more money to compensate for its depreciated currency and reduced buying power. Japan&#39;s increasingly difficult financial situation only makes the politics over financing its defense buildup a more sensitive and challenging matter.</p><h4> <strong>Japan&#39;s role in Indo-Pacific security</strong></h4><p> Despite these hurdles, Japan has managed to play a pivotal role and see notable successes in regional security. Japan&#39;s role is part of a broader and sophisticated effort to coordinate military efforts with allies and partners in the region to enhance deterrence against Chinese aggression and promote a peaceful Indo-Pacific region. This overlapping effort is one of the least understood, most complex and consequential trends in defense diplomacy.</p><p> Among its substantial efforts, Japan helps facilitate overlapping defense cooperation. Within the last year, Tokyo has signed significant reciprocal access agreements with <a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/International-relations/Indo-Pacific/Japan-and-U.K.-sign-landmark-defense-cooperation-treaty">the United Kingdom</a> and <a href="https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/International-relations/Indo-Pacific/U.S.-cements-game-changing-defense-ties-with-Australia-Japan">Australia</a> . Together with an existing agreement with the US, these agreements allow each country&#39;s armed forces to train and operate on Japanese soil. A reciprocal agreement is also being negotiated with <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/japan-france-leaders-vow-strengthen-ties-paris-eyes-more-access-2023-05-19/">France</a> , further expanding Japan&#39;s coordinator role for foreign militaries. Another agreement under negotiation with US ally, the Philippines, would allow Japanese troops to <a href="https://www.ft.com/content/2bf4cb90-bc86-4db2-a0d5-21973f7b2765">operate on Philippine territory</a> in the strategically critical South China Sea.</p><p> These agreements enhance interoperability and signal a unified stance against aggression, significantly bolstering regional deterrence and stability. The coordination meshwork means different partner militaries can train and operate on Japanese soil at the same time, enabling a higher degree of coordination with a larger number of armed forces close to China&#39;s waters. While signaling deterrence, peacefully managing the relationship with China for Japan is still highly important. Prime Minister Kishida&#39;s last meeting with Xi Jinping reaffirmed the two nations&#39; <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/us/japan-pm-kishida-hold-talks-with-chinas-xi-nov-16-nikkei-2023-11-16/">“strategic relationship.”</a> Overlapping defense diplomacy is helping to enhance deterrence and promote a peaceful regional status quo.</p><p> This meshwork extends beyond Japanese soil with maritime cooperation. In a past project I originated for CNBC, I anticipated <a href="https://www.cnbc.com/quad-summit-and-china-game-theory-predictions-for-the-future-of-the-quad/">the extent of maritime coordination</a> between Japan and other countries, while managing a continuing relationship with China. The larger implication is significant and poorly understood by experts because interaction with China is dynamic. The closer defense coordination helps promote regional peace from a shared mission, integrated defense efforts and increased costs associated with potential conflict. Japan&#39;s defense buildup helps with these aims by supplementing coalition defense might. Whether Japan will be able to fully capitalize on its international leadership will require overcoming the challenges with its buildup.</p><h4> <strong>Japan&#39;s critical decision point</strong></h4><p> As Japan stands at a crucial juncture in its defense strategy, the decisions made now will shape its future capabilities and influence in the Indo-Pacific. These decisions will not only affect Japan&#39;s security but also have significant implications for its role in regional security. With time running out and financial uncertainties looming, the stakes are high. The Japanese government faces a tumultuous political environment at home, severe financial constraints and a lack of decisive leadership. As an election year approaches, leaders balancing domestic and international politics must navigate these challenges decisively.</p><p> Action is required for Tokyo to secure the necessary financing, driven by national and regional security. In this high-stakes defense dilemma, it is crucial to recognize that leaders typically act in their self-interest. This self-interest has already led to a lack of decisive leadership regarding defense funding amidst an unprecedented government corruption scandal. To address Japan&#39;s defense challenges effectively, leaders&#39; motivations must align with national defense. Whether this alignment happens will be a guiding north star during a pivotal election year, determining whether Japan can achieve its defense ambitions or face significant compromises. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/a-pivotal-moment-for-japans-national?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/a-pivotal-moment-for-japans-national?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p>; 
How to devalue the dollarTrump and Lighthizer want to "weaken" the dollar. It's an idea worth considering, but the devil is in the details. https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/how-to-devalue-the-dollar https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/how-to-devalue-the-dollarNoah Smith Fri, 24 May 2024 21:02:21 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F33cc74b7-4d50-4f9b-9d6e-4a14c29f05ab_1024x768.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F33cc74b7-4d50-4f9b-9d6e-4a14c29f05ab_1024x768.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F33cc74b7-4d50-4f9b-9d6e-4a14c29f05ab_1024x768.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F33cc74b7-4d50-4f9b-9d6e-4a14c29f05ab_1024x768.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F33cc74b7-4d50-4f9b-9d6e-4a14c29f05ab_1024x768.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F33cc74b7-4d50-4f9b-9d6e-4a14c29f05ab_1024x768.jpeg" width="718" height="538.5" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/33cc74b7-4d50-4f9b-9d6e-4a14c29f05ab_1024x768.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:768,&quot;width&quot;:1024,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:718,&quot;bytes&quot;:256633,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F33cc74b7-4d50-4f9b-9d6e-4a14c29f05ab_1024x768.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F33cc74b7-4d50-4f9b-9d6e-4a14c29f05ab_1024x768.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F33cc74b7-4d50-4f9b-9d6e-4a14c29f05ab_1024x768.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F33cc74b7-4d50-4f9b-9d6e-4a14c29f05ab_1024x768.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line><figcaption class="image-caption"> &quot; <a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/59937401@N07/5857169353">Dollar Bill Cut in Half</a> &quot; by <a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/59937401@N07">Images_of_Money</a> , <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/?ref=openverse">CC BY 2.0</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> The other day I was chatting with a politician (who shall remain nameless), and he was telling me how worried he was about China. We talked about the risk of war, and about manufacturing jobs lost to Chinese competition. But then he said something unexpected. “I think their ultimate goal,” he muttered darkly, “is to bring down the dollar.”</p><p> I&#39;ll talk about that idea in a bit, but what really struck me was just how reflexively many Americans associate the strength of their currency with the strength of their nation.我不太确定为什么。 It might be just an unfortunate misunderstanding of the word “strength”. In fact, dollar “strength” is just a colloquial term — what it means is that the dollar is <em>expensive</em> relative to other currencies. Alternatively, people might realize that the dollar tends to be strong when the US economy is doing well, and assume correlation equals causation. Or maybe Americans are just proud of how many people around the world want to hold their currency.</p><p> Whatever the reason, I know two people who don&#39;t think a “strong” dollar is a good idea: Donald Trump and his main trade adviser, Robert Lighthizer. <a href="https://foreignpolicy.com/2024/05/18/robert-lighthizer-trump-election-trade-tariffs-treasury-secretary/">Trump is promising to weaken the dollar</a> if he gets back into office, and Lighthizer appears to be the one who came up with the idea:</p><blockquote><p> Lighthizer himself has been counseling Trump to <a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2024/04/15/devaluing-dollar-trump-trade-war-00152009#:~:text=Advisers%20close%20to%20the%20former,exports%20but%20also%20fuel%20inflation.">devalue the strong US dollar</a> if he is elected in order to boost US exports—advice that has been widely read as an audition for the Treasury post…</p><p> [Lighthizer] would make it a goal of US policy to balance trade with the rest of the world, not just China. The implications are enormous. One tool, which Lighthizer has <a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2024/04/15/devaluing-dollar-trump-trade-war-00152009">reportedly proposed</a> to Trump, is a concerted effort to weaken the US dollar against other currencies. Other things being equal, a cheaper dollar would reduce the prices that foreigners pay for US exports, make imports more expensive for Americans, and help bring trade closer to balance. The dollar, however, has long been overvalued, partly because of its role as the global currency of choice; more recently, it has been soaring in response to a strong US economy and conflicts in the Middle East and Europe that have sent investors running for the safe haven of US assets. Details are scant, but Lighthizer appears to be envisioning a reprise of actions taken by US President Richard Nixon in 1971 and Ronald Reagan in 1987: imposing or threatening tariffs on trading partners unless they agree to take steps to revalue their currencies against the dollar.</p></blockquote><p> This would be a huge change to the global financial system — and to the US economy. That doesn&#39;t mean it would be a <em>bad</em> change. Lighthizer is right that “weakening” the dollar to some extent would likely make US exports more competitive in world markets, and help rebalance the US economy toward manufacturing and away from finance. And in the long run, it could help stabilize the global financial system.</p><p> But there are plenty of dangers involved as well. A cheaper dollar would almost certainly fuel higher inflation. It&#39;s also easy to overshoot — a dollar that was <em>too</em> cheap would make life a lot harder for US manufacturers who need to import components and materials. And most of the methods that the US could use to depreciate the dollar are either of questionable effectiveness or would risk big problems in the financial system.</p><p> In any case, this is Trump&#39;s biggest and most important economic proposal — bigger than tariffs by far. So I thought I should write an explainer about this whole issue — why the dollar is “strong” in the first place, the costs and benefits of a “strong” dollar, how the dollar might be depreciated, and what this would mean for Americans and for the world.</p><h4> The basics: Why the dollar is “strong”, and what that means for Americans</h4><div class="paywall-jump" data-component-name="PaywallToDOM"></div><p> The key to understanding international economics is to understand this one simple fact: <strong>If you want to buy something a country produces, you need that country&#39;s currency.</strong></p><p> Think about this for a second. Suppose I have a business in Japan that makes zippers. Why am I selling zippers? To make money so I can buy stuff. But to me, “money” means “yen”, and the stuff I want to buy — ramen, rent for my Tokyo apartment, day care for my kids, etc. — is priced in yen. So if you want to buy my zippers, whether you&#39;re in Tokyo, Mumbai, or in Wichita, Kansas, you need some yen.</p><p> But if you&#39;re in Mumbai or Wichita, you don&#39;t have a bunch of yen just lying around. You need to go get some. So you go to a <em>foreign exchange market</em> , and you swap your rupees or your dollars for yen.</p><p> The yen&#39;s value, in terms of rupees or dollars, will be determined by how many people do this, and how many rupees or dollars they swap for yen. In other words, the value of the yen is determined by <em>supply and demand</em> . Every time someone swaps their dollars for yen to buy a Japanese-made zipper, the demand for yen goes up a little bit, and the yen gets a little bit more expensive — ie, “stronger” — as a result.</p><p> Now, I used zippers as an example, but goods and services aren&#39;t the only things you can buy from a foreign country. You can also buy <em>financial assets</em> — bonds, stocks, real estate, and so on. If the Japanese zipper company issues a bond denominated in yen, and you want to buy it, you&#39;re going to need yen in order to buy that bond. So demand for financial assets can also create demand for a currency, and make it more expensive (“stronger”).</p><p> Now here&#39;s the thing — when a country&#39;s exchange rate gets “stronger”, it makes that country&#39;s exports more expensive to buy. If there&#39;s a huge demand for a country&#39;s bonds, that will make its currency more expensive. And because its currency is more expensive, it will find it harder to export goods and services.</p><p> This is the most common explanation for why the US runs a large <em>trade deficit</em> — somewhere around 3% of GDP <a class="footnote-anchor" data-component-name="FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id="footnote-anchor-1" href="#footnote-1" target="_self">1</a> : </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbb192f38-fdc6-40d9-9278-6f4d61e6a990_1318x450.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbb192f38-fdc6-40d9-9278-6f4d61e6a990_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbb192f38-fdc6-40d9-9278-6f4d61e6a990_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbb192f38-fdc6-40d9-9278-6f4d61e6a990_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbb192f38-fdc6-40d9-9278-6f4d61e6a990_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbb192f38-fdc6-40d9-9278-6f4d61e6a990_1318x450.png" width="1318" height="450" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bb192f38-fdc6-40d9-9278-6f4d61e6a990_1318x450.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:450,&quot;width&quot;:1318,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:62307,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbb192f38-fdc6-40d9-9278-6f4d61e6a990_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbb192f38-fdc6-40d9-9278-6f4d61e6a990_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbb192f38-fdc6-40d9-9278-6f4d61e6a990_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbb192f38-fdc6-40d9-9278-6f4d61e6a990_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p> The US dollar functions as the world&#39;s most important <em>reserve currency</em> . That means that a whole bunch of countries around the world hold a whole bunch of US bonds — mostly through their central banks. The foreign-currency bonds held by central banks are called “foreign exchange reserves”, “forex reserves”, or just “reserves”. When we say that most “reserves” around the world are “in dollars”, or that the dollar is “the reserve currency”, what we mean is that most of the foreign-currency bonds that central banks hold are US bonds. In this case, “most” actually means around 60%: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F84ec93bc-98b4-4e37-94cf-a8ebae4311af_1308x546.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F84ec93bc-98b4-4e37-94cf-a8ebae4311af_1308x546.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F84ec93bc-98b4-4e37-94cf-a8ebae4311af_1308x546.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F84ec93bc-98b4-4e37-94cf-a8ebae4311af_1308x546.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F84ec93bc-98b4-4e37-94cf-a8ebae4311af_1308x546.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F84ec93bc-98b4-4e37-94cf-a8ebae4311af_1308x546.jpeg" width="1308" height="546" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/84ec93bc-98b4-4e37-94cf-a8ebae4311af_1308x546.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:546,&quot;width&quot;:1308,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:107446,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F84ec93bc-98b4-4e37-94cf-a8ebae4311af_1308x546.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F84ec93bc-98b4-4e37-94cf-a8ebae4311af_1308x546.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F84ec93bc-98b4-4e37-94cf-a8ebae4311af_1308x546.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F84ec93bc-98b4-4e37-94cf-a8ebae4311af_1308x546.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://data.imf.org/?sk=e6a5f467-c14b-4aa8-9f6d-5a09ec4e62a4">IMF</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> So there&#39;s a lot of demand out there in the world for US bonds. But to buy those bonds, the countries that bought the reserves had to swap their own currencies for dollars. That made the dollar more expensive and the other countries&#39; currencies cheaper. And that made those countries&#39; exports of goods and services more competitive, and US exports less competitive. In other words, <em>demand for US bonds crowded out demand for US goods and services</em> .</p><p> This makes life harder for US manufacturers and providers of tradable services, because it makes them less competitive. It makes <em>cheap imports</em> — especially cheap Chinese imports — even cheaper, which makes it very hard to keep factories in the US And the resulting decline of US manufacturing weakened our military&#39;s ability to produce a bunch of weapons in case of a major war.</p><p> But at the same time, the “strong” dollar makes it easier for Americans to afford cheap imported goods, which lets them consume more. And many economists also believe that it lowers US interest rates, make it easier for Americans to borrow money. <em>Easy borrowing</em> can boost consumption (at least in the short term), and it also gives a boost to the finance industry, which relies on a lot of borrowing in order to operate. Finally, it makes it easier for the US government to levy financial sanctions on other countries, as we did against Russia and Iran.</p><p> So there are winners and losers from the “strong” dollar. That&#39;s why I don&#39;t like the word “strong” here — an expensive dollar makes American consumers and financiers and sanctions stronger, but it makes exporters, manufacturers, and the military weaker.</p><p> Now, here are two important things we <em>don&#39;t</em> actually know:</p><ol><li><p> We don&#39;t know <em>why</em> all these countries want all these US bonds.</p></li><li><p> We don&#39;t know <em>how much</em> of the US trade deficit is caused by overseas demand for US bonds.</p></li></ol><p> There are several theories for why countries&#39; central banks want to hold US bonds, and all of them could potentially be true at once. One theory is that other countries buy US bonds in order to <em>intentionally keep their currencies cheap</em> , so they can export more stuff, because they think exporting more stuff will help their economies in the long run. Another theory is that these US bonds act as <em>a form of insurance</em> against <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-sri-lanka-is-having-an-economic">currency crises</a> — if your currency depreciates so much that you have trouble affording imports of food and fuel, you can sell some of your dollar reserves to prop up the value of your currency 。 A third theory is that because dollars are often <em>used in trade and international finance</em> , other countries want to keep some US bonds around so they can sell them for dollars in order to buy imports. There are some other theories too.</p><p> Whatever the reason, it&#39;s likely that the robust international demand for US bonds makes the US dollar more expensive relative to other currencies. How <em>much</em> more expensive, we don&#39;t know. But if you want to reduce the US trade deficit and/or make American exports more competitive on world markets — two different but related goals — then the dollar&#39;s role as the “reserve currency” is one big obstacle standing in your way. As long as a bunch of foreign central banks are out there buying US bonds, the US dollar will always be an expensive currency, making it an uphill battle to sell more American stuff overseas or to even out the balance of trade.</p><p> That is why Robert Lighthizer, who cares a whole lot about trade deficits, <a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2024/04/15/devaluing-dollar-trump-trade-war-00152009#:~:text=Advisers%20close%20to%20the%20former,exports%20but%20also%20fuel%20inflation.">wants to devalue the US dollar</a> . And that&#39;s also why anyone who cares about preserving and expanding US industrial capacity — which now includes many progressives <em>and</em> many conservatives — will inevitably have to think about the dollar&#39;s value as well.</p><h4> How would a dollar depreciation work in practice?</h4><p> If you want your currency to get cheaper, there are a few basic things you can do.这些包括：</p><ol><li><p> Having the central bank print money (lower interest rates)</p></li><li><p> Getting Americans to save more</p></li><li><p> Having the central bank buy foreign currency (currency intervention)</p></li><li><p> Pressuring foreign countries to appreciate their currencies against the dollar</p></li><li><p> Putting restrictions on foreigners buying US bonds (capital controls)</p></li></ol><p> Menzie Chinn has <a href="https://econbrowser.com/archives/2024/05/hi-ho-hi-ho-its-off-to-fx-war-we-go">a great blog post</a> in which he discusses options (1), (3), and (4) on this list, and includes some useful research papers for reference. Anyway, let&#39;s go through these options and list their strengths and drawbacks.</p><h5> <strong>Printing money / Lower interest rates</strong></h5><p> First, remember that the value of the dollar in foreign exchange markets is determined by supply and demand for dollars. I&#39;ve talked entirely about the demand side, but the supply side is also important. If you increase the supply of dollars in the world, that should drive the price of dollars (ie the exchange rate) down. So the Fed could just print a bunch of money in an attempt to devalue the dollar. This would lower interest rates, which would make buying US bonds a worse deal financially. Presumably, that would get some countries to buy fewer US bonds, thus depreciating the dollar.</p><p> There are a couple problems with this. First, printing a bunch of money would cause a bunch of inflation, which Americans are already very mad about. Second, the main trade deficit we care about is the one with China, and the country whose exports we care most about competing with is China. In fact, almost all of the trade imbalance in the world, if you count the EU as one country, is just a US trade deficit matched with a Chinese trade surplus: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf670593-f20c-47b2-ae9e-c742d33f4038_1422x1033.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf670593-f20c-47b2-ae9e-c742d33f4038_1422x1033.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf670593-f20c-47b2-ae9e-c742d33f4038_1422x1033.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf670593-f20c-47b2-ae9e-c742d33f4038_1422x1033.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf670593-f20c-47b2-ae9e-c742d33f4038_1422x1033.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf670593-f20c-47b2-ae9e-c742d33f4038_1422x1033.jpeg" width="1422" height="1033" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/df670593-f20c-47b2-ae9e-c742d33f4038_1422x1033.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1033,&quot;width&quot;:1422,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:267908,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf670593-f20c-47b2-ae9e-c742d33f4038_1422x1033.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf670593-f20c-47b2-ae9e-c742d33f4038_1422x1033.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf670593-f20c-47b2-ae9e-c742d33f4038_1422x1033.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf670593-f20c-47b2-ae9e-c742d33f4038_1422x1033.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://x.com/Brad_Setser/status/1762614544520851918">Brad Setser</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> China&#39;s central bank probably cares about financial gains and losses a lot less than the central banks of America&#39;s allies in Europe, Asia, etc. So printing money would probably not be as effective in bringing down the US-China trade deficit — it would only affect our much smaller deficits with countries like Korea, Taiwan, and Germany, weakening those allies&#39; export competitiveness while not doing much to China.</p><p> So causing inflation in the US while not doing much to change the US/China trade balance doesn&#39;t sound like a great idea. Unsurprisingly, I don&#39;t see anyone suggesting this.</p><h5> Getting Americans to save more</h5><p> A second idea — which Chinn doesn&#39;t mention, but which Miles Kimball, who taught me about 2/3 of what you&#39;re reading in this blog post, thought we should do — is to get Americans to save more money. If American households and American companies bought more US bonds, that would make them more expensive (ie it will lower interest rates). And it would do so in a way that doesn&#39;t cause inflation, because when Americans save more, it means they consume less, so aggregate demand would fall.</p><p> Currently, the US doesn&#39;t save much <a href="https://worldpopulationreview.com/country-rankings/savings-rate-by-country">compared to a lot of other countries</a> , especially China. We might be able to use policy to boost that amount. The question is “How?”. For many years, economists believed that policies like capital gains tax cuts and tax credits for 401k&#39;s and other things like that would get Americans to save more. But if they did, it sure didn&#39;t show up in the aggregate statistics. Personal savings rates have gone mostly down over the years: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb07151ba-d434-409f-9e34-3779c552c53f_1318x450.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb07151ba-d434-409f-9e34-3779c552c53f_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb07151ba-d434-409f-9e34-3779c552c53f_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb07151ba-d434-409f-9e34-3779c552c53f_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb07151ba-d434-409f-9e34-3779c552c53f_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb07151ba-d434-409f-9e34-3779c552c53f_1318x450.png" width="1318" height="450" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b07151ba-d434-409f-9e34-3779c552c53f_1318x450.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:450,&quot;width&quot;:1318,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:66331,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb07151ba-d434-409f-9e34-3779c552c53f_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb07151ba-d434-409f-9e34-3779c552c53f_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb07151ba-d434-409f-9e34-3779c552c53f_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb07151ba-d434-409f-9e34-3779c552c53f_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p> Corporate savings rates haven&#39;t really changed much either. So it&#39;s just not clear how to get the US to save more money. One option is deep fiscal austerity, but that&#39;s politically tough, especially at the scale you&#39;d have to do it in order to affect the exchange rate.</p><p> And on top of all that, saving more, like printing money, would only reduce our deficit with China if China&#39;s central bank cared a lot about the interest rate it&#39;s getting on US bonds. It probably does <em>not</em> care a lot. So savings inducement is probably a very costly policy for not a lot of gain in terms of exchange rate changes.</p><h5> Sterilized currency intervention</h5><p> A third alternative is to have the Fed print money and use it to buy Chinese assets — yuan-denominated bonds, Chinese stocks, real estate, etc. That&#39;s called currency intervention, or forex intervention. It&#39;s what China does to us — it&#39;s how they accumulated all those dollar reserves in the first place. We could just do it right back to them.</p><p> If the Fed just did this without doing anything else, it would reduce interest rates and cause a big increase in the supply of dollars, which would raise the risk of inflation, as I mentioned above. That&#39;s called “unsterilized intervention”. But if the Fed bought Chinese assets while also selling US bonds at the same time, the effects on inflation and interest rates would cancel out. That&#39;s called “sterilized intervention”.</p><p> Menzie Chinn <a href="https://econbrowser.com/archives/2024/05/hi-ho-hi-ho-its-off-to-fx-war-we-go">writes</a> that “there&#39;s not much evidence that for countries with open capital markets this works, on an extended basis,” and sends us to <a href="https://users.ssc.wisc.edu/~mchinn/Popper_FXI_apr22.pdf">a literature survey by Popper (2022)</a> . But Popper doesn&#39;t really conclude much either way — getting convincing empirical evidence for macro stuff like this is inherently hard, because there&#39;s no real way to isolate causality. So I don&#39;t think we really know if this would work, and there&#39;s <a href="https://www.imf.org/en/Publications/WP/Issues/2020/07/07/A-Conceptual-Model-for-the-Integrated-Policy-Framework-49558">some theory indicating it might</a> . But the unknowns are large.</p><p> In any case, I think sterilized intervention is by far the most promising policy tool in the list, and it&#39;s the one we should be looking at. It would require some legal changes, both to allow the Fed to do it, and to mandate that it do it. But the low risk of inflation, and the fact that we could target the policy specifically to China, make it a pretty attractive option.</p><h5> Pressuring other countries to devalue their currencies</h5><p> But anyway, let&#39;s move on and talk about what Robert Lighthizer actually seems to have in mind — pressuring foreign governments to devalue their currencies. Basically, this means we would sit down in a room with the other countries and say “OK guys, you need to stop buying so many US bonds. In fact, sell off the ones you have, until your currency gets more expensive relative to the dollar.”</p><p> In fact, we&#39;ve done this once before, in 1985. It was called <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plaza_Accord">the Plaza Accord</a> . We successfully pressured European allies and Japan into appreciating their currencies relative to the dollar, and the dollar did in fact get “weaker”. And although <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plaza_Accord#Objective_failure">people debate</a> how effective it was, the general consensus is that the Plaza Accord largely succeeded in <a href="https://www.macrotrends.net/global-metrics/countries/USA/united-states/trade-balance-deficit#google_vignette">reducing the small US trade deficit</a> of the 1980s. <a class="footnote-anchor" data-component-name="FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id="footnote-anchor-2" href="#footnote-2" target="_self">2</a></p><p> So this would actually be a very promising avenue for devaluing the dollar safely, if not for one big problem: The only trading partner that really matters, ie China, is <em>not going to do agree to this</em> like America&#39;s allies did in 1985.</p><p> Chinese leaders <a href="https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2019/05/23/as-the-trade-war-heats-up-china-looks-to-japans-past-for-lessons">reportedly believe</a> that the Plaza Accord was what derailed Japan&#39;s economy and caused its decades of stagnation. That is probably false — in fact, the Plaza Accord completely <em>failed</em> to reduce America&#39;s bilateral trade deficit with Japan. All of the trade deficit reduction came from Europe. But China&#39;s leaders <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-is-china-producing-so-many-export">appear to believe</a> that a big trade surplus is in their national interest, and that appreciating their currency would represent knuckling under to US pressure, and so they&#39;re just <a href="http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/31/c_137433229.htm">not going to do it</a> .</p><p> Which means that a “Plaza Accord 2.0”, as Lighthizer seems to be planning, would be aimed entirely at America&#39;s Asian and European allies — whose trade surpluses with the US are very small. If Japan, Taiwan, Korea, etc. appreciated their currencies and China didn&#39;t, it would simply hurt America&#39;s allies and strengthen China. This might count as a “win” in Robert Lighthizer&#39;s mind, but in reality it would be a loss for the US</p><h5> Capital controls</h5><p> There&#39;s one more option I could mention, even though it&#39;s incredibly unlikely to happen. Everything I&#39;ve talked about so far is true in a world of <em>free capital movement</em> — in other words, it assumes there&#39;s a “foreign exchange market” where you can just swap dollars for yen, yen for rupees, rupees for euros, and so在。 But some countries restrict their citizens and their companies from buying and selling foreign currencies. These restrictions are called “capital controls”. China has capital controls, but currently the US does not.</p><p> The US could enact capital controls, ending the system of floating exchange rates and more-or-less free capital movement that has prevailed since 1973. We could enact a law restricting foreign purchases of US bonds, or putting a tax on those purchases. The only person I&#39;ve seen suggest this is <a href="https://carnegieendowment.org/china-financial-markets/2024/02/can-trade-intervention-lead-to-freer-trade?lang=en">Michael Pettis</a> :</p><blockquote><p> [A] more direct and focused alternative to tariffs is capital controls. If the United States were to tax capital inflows, or otherwise restrict capital inflows from surplus economies, then there would be no need for the US trade account and its domestic savings rates to adjust to net foreign inflows. There would also be no need for import tariffs.</p></blockquote><p> This would work, though it would take lots of time and effort to implement. And it would cause a wrenching change to our entire economic and financial system.</p><p> And in the end, there&#39;s no guarantee that it would reduce our bilateral trade deficit with China — the entire brunt of the adjustment might fall on US allies, who might be forced to run trade <em>deficits</em> against the US in order to balance out China&#39;s trade surplus 。 This is especially likely because China&#39;s government would be by far the most willing — and able — to pay the tax for buying US bonds. So it would likely keep buying bonds, while other countries would be forced to stop.</p><p> If reducing the US&#39; overall trade deficit is your overriding goal, that counts as a “win”. But if your goal is to strengthen the export industries of the US-led geopolitical bloc relative to China, that would not be a good outcome.</p><h4> General costs and risks of dollar devaluation</h4><p> So of all the options on the table, sterilized intervention — having the Fed buy Chinese assets and sell US bonds — seems like the best. Unfortunately, no one is talking about it. And all the other options seem much more likely to punch down on America&#39;s allies, whose economies are already much weaker than our own, while doing relatively little to address the central problem of the bilateral deficit with China.</p><p> Also, it&#39;s worth mentioning that any policy to devalue the dollar would inevitably come with some costs and risks. For one thing, dollar devaluation would make imports more expensive for Americans. Another way of putting this is that the US&#39; trade deficit allows it to increase consumption — not by a huge amount, maybe only 4%, but enough to notice.</p><p> More importantly, dollar devaluation could put a lot of strain on the American financial system. It&#39;s not just foreign governments who hold US bonds — in fact, most of those bonds are held domestically, especially by US banks. Devaluing the dollar would lead to lower demand for US bonds, which could drop their price by a little or a lot. This might not be a big danger — in 2015, China <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2016-02-29/capital-flight-delivers-a-verdict-on-china-s-economy?sref=R8NfLgwS">sold off a substantial portion</a> of its dollar reserves, and the value of US bonds didn&#39;t really shift (in econ jargon, total demand turned out to be highly inelastic). But if this time turned out differently, it could hurt the balance sheets of many US banks — recall that a decrease in the value of government bonds <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-was-there-a-run-on-silicon-valley">almost caused a banking crisis</a> back in 2023.</p><p> These costs and risks are why, frankly, I don&#39;t expect Trump to actually implement any of Lighthizer&#39;s proposals. Trump would be afraid that anything that caused inflation would lose him popular support. And because he built his own fortune on cheap loans, he&#39;s unlikely to embrace any policy that would cut off major sources of cheap loans from abroad. Also, the TikTok affair showed that Trump is <a href="https://time.com/6900348/tiktok-ban-donald-trump-congress/">easily pressured</a> by China and its proxies.</p><p> But if Biden wins, or if someone else serious gets into office, I would take a look at sterilized currency intervention as a way to nudge China toward appreciating its currency.</p><p>谁知道呢？ A nudge might be all it takes. My analysis above was predicated on the idea that China&#39;s leaders don&#39;t <em>want</em> to appreciate the yuan. China&#39;s leaders basically don&#39;t do anything they don&#39;t want to do. But they might <em>change their mind</em> about what&#39;s in their own best interests.</p><p> In fact, their mind might already be in the process of changing. The US financial sanctions on Russia have motivated China to start <a href="https://www.wsj.com/finance/currencies/chinas-yuan-is-quietly-gaining-ground-f0b8994b">using more yuan in its foreign trade</a> and fewer dollars, in order to reduce its own vulnerability to a similar attack. That effort is still in its infancy, but if it continues, it&#39;ll reduce Chinese demand for dollars somewhat. Meanwhile, China is buying up <a href="https://www.axios.com/2024/04/08/gold-record-highs">massive amounts of gold</a> , signaling its shift away from US bonds as the core of its reserves. It may even be <a href="https://www.reuters.com/markets/asia/chinas-us-bond-shifts-put-dollar-under-geopolitical-spotlight-2024-05-21/">selling down some</a> of its US bond holdings, though it&#39;s hard to tell; it might just be having its state-owned banks <a href="https://www.cfr.org/blog/chinas-new-currency-playbook">buy more to compensate</a> .</p><p> But in any case, these are signs that China&#39;s leaders are growing less content with a global financial order in which they depend on the hegemony of the US dollar. A nudge, in terms of a well-timed currency intervention by the US government — or even a few more <a href="https://www.wsj.com/politics/national-security/u-s-takes-aim-at-chinese-banks-aiding-russia-war-effort-fcf76dcc">well-placed financial sanctions</a> on Chinse companies that supply Russia&#39;s war effort — might help accelerate this shift in their thinking. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/how-to-devalue-the-dollar?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/how-to-devalue-the-dollar?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><div class="footnote" data-component-name="FootnoteToDOM"><a id="footnote-1" href="#footnote-anchor-1" class="footnote-number" contenteditable="false" target="_self">1</a><div class="footnote-content"><p> A portion of this trade deficit is fake, for two reasons. First, US companies <a href="https://www.cbo.gov/system/files/2019-05/55284-Transfer%20Pricing-WP.pdf">pretend that they make their profits overseas</a> , in order to avoid taxes. Second, the trade deficit doesn&#39;t take value-added trade into account — it only measures where things were assembled, not where the value of their components and designs was created. But even netting out those two things, the US trade deficit is still quite large.</p></div></div><div class="footnote" data-component-name="FootnoteToDOM"> <a id="footnote-2" href="#footnote-anchor-2" class="footnote-number" contenteditable="false" target="_self">2</a><div class="footnote-content"><p> In fact, it took until 1987 for the trade deficit to start falling. This is because when a country&#39;s currency gets weaker, it takes years for exports to rise and imports to fall as a result. But what happens immediately is that imports get more expensive, which temporarily raise the trade deficit. These are called the “quantity effect” and the “valuation effect”. Eventually the quantity effect should overwhelm the valuation effect, but it takes time.</p></div></div> ;
How liberal democracy might lose the 21st centuryA scary little theory about information and freedom. https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/how-liberal-democracy-might-lose https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/how-liberal-democracy-might-loseNoah Smith Wed, 22 May 2024 21:49:31 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba726358-dce3-4784-82a3-5c71fbb1ca03_1200x578.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba726358-dce3-4784-82a3-5c71fbb1ca03_1200x578.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba726358-dce3-4784-82a3-5c71fbb1ca03_1200x578.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba726358-dce3-4784-82a3-5c71fbb1ca03_1200x578.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba726358-dce3-4784-82a3-5c71fbb1ca03_1200x578.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba726358-dce3-4784-82a3-5c71fbb1ca03_1200x578.jpeg" width="1200" height="578" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ba726358-dce3-4784-82a3-5c71fbb1ca03_1200x578.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:578,&quot;width&quot;:1200,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:83339,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba726358-dce3-4784-82a3-5c71fbb1ca03_1200x578.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba726358-dce3-4784-82a3-5c71fbb1ca03_1200x578.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba726358-dce3-4784-82a3-5c71fbb1ca03_1200x578.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fba726358-dce3-4784-82a3-5c71fbb1ca03_1200x578.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></figure></div><p> I was raised in an age of liberal triumphalism. Liberal democracy won the 20th century — imperialism, fascism, and communism all collapsed, and by the end of the century the US and its democratic allies in Asia and Europe were both economically and militarily ascendant. Even China, which remained an autocracy, liberalized its economy and parts of its society during this time. Even scholars who turned up their noses at Francis Fukuyama&#39;s “end of history” were generally favorable to arguments that capitalism and/or liberal democracy fostered <a href="https://pages.ucsd.edu/~egartzke/publications/gartzke_ajps_07.pdf">peace</a> , <a href="https://www.bu.edu/sthacker/files/2012/01/Democracy-and-Human-Development.pdf">happiness</a> , and <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1540-5907.2007.00299.x">prosperity</a> . There was an overwhelming sense that freedom — the freedom to speak your mind, to live as you liked, to buy and sell what you wished — was <em>the thing that won</em> .</p><p> Just two decades later, that idea is deeply in doubt. The wave of democratization and social liberalization <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-darkness">went into reverse</a> . The US has been riven by social and political chaos, and its weaknesses in manufacturing and homebuilding have been starkly exposed. Meanwhile China, the <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/china-at-the-peak">ascendant superpower</a> of the early 21st century, has <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/2024-governing-china-after-the-boom/?sref=R8NfLgwS">moved back toward</a> a more dirigiste economy and a more totalitarian society under Xi Jinping.</p><p> A number of people I know who travel to China these days come back with starry-eyed tales of how wonderful it is compared to the US: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F598ab4db-2e5a-4850-b29a-9511471f7c8e_656x839.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F598ab4db-2e5a-4850-b29a-9511471f7c8e_656x839.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image